<p><i><b>Ishmael</b></i> is a 1992 <a href="/wiki/Novel" title="Novel">novel</a> by <a href="/wiki/Daniel_Quinn" title="Daniel Quinn">Daniel Quinn</a>. It examines <a href="/wiki/Mythology" title="Mythology">mythology</a>, its effect on <a href="/wiki/Ethics_(philosophy)" title="Ethics (philosophy)" class="mw-redirect">ethics</a>, and how that relates to <a href="/wiki/Sustainability" title="Sustainability">sustainability</a>. The novel uses a style of <a href="/wiki/Socratic_dialogue" title="Socratic dialogue">Socratic dialogue</a> to deconstruct the notion of <a href="/wiki/Human_supremacy" title="Human supremacy" class="mw-redirect">human supremacy</a>, or that humans are the end product, the pinnacle of biological evolution, as a cultural myth, and asserts that modern civilization is "enacting" that myth.</p>
<p><i>Ishmael</i> was awarded the $500,000 <a href="/wiki/Turner_Tomorrow_Fellowship_Award" title="Turner Tomorrow Fellowship Award">Turner Tomorrow Fellowship Award</a>. The book is the first of a <a href="/wiki/Trilogy" title="Trilogy">trilogy</a> including <i><a href="/wiki/The_Story_of_B" title="The Story of B">The Story of B</a></i> and <i><a href="/wiki/My_Ishmael" title="My Ishmael">My Ishmael</a></i>.</p>
